✅ Canonical Orion Product Structure (LOCK THIS)
Use this exact structure, in this order, for each Orion product (starting with CareLink SmartSync™ Azure Astra Application).

0. Product Identity (Metadata – Very Short)
Purpose: grounding + retrieval accuracy.
Include:
Product Name
Product Type (Application / Platform Service / Legacy System)
Orion Tier (Platform / Tier‑1 / Tier‑2 / Stub)
Deployment Model (Cloud / Edge / Hybrid)
Current Status (Active / Legacy / Transitional)
This section should be factual, minimal, and stable.

1. Purpose & Context (WHY IT EXISTS)
This is the most important section for explanation quality.
Answer explicitly:
What problem this product exists to solve
Who it is for (clinicians, systems, enterprise)
Why Orion needed this product
What would break or regress if it didn’t exist
✅ Use causal language
❌ Avoid marketing or feature lists
Example style:
“This product exists because legacy systems could not…”

2. Core Problems Solved (BOUNDARY OF VALUE)
Define what it does solve vs what it does not try to solve.
Include:
Primary problem domains (e.g., device communication, session management)
Secondary problems it supports
Problems intentionally out of scope (brief mention)
This teaches the LLM where to stop.

3. High‑Level Architecture Overview (TEXT‑ONLY)
Explain the architecture in words, not components lists.
Include:
Major layers (device, edge, cloud, integration)
Responsibility of each layer
How responsibilities are separated
Where trust boundaries exist
✅ Narrative form
❌ “Component A → Component B” lists without explanation

4. Key System Components & Responsibilities
Now you may enumerate components, but always with responsibility framing.
For each component:
What it is responsible for
What it explicitly does NOT do
What it depends on
This section enables:
deep follow‑ups
“what happens if X fails?” questions

5. Core Workflows (SYSTEM BEHAVIOR)
Describe end‑to‑end workflows, not features.
Examples:
Session lifecycle
Authentication & authorization flow
Data ingestion and persistence flow
Error or failure handling (high level)
Each workflow should explain:
Trigger
Major steps
Completion condition
Safety or validation checks
This is where Orion becomes understandable.

6. Data Concepts & Metrics (CONCEPTUAL ONLY)
Explain:
Key data entities (sessions, devices, users, events)
How they relate conceptually
Important metrics and what they mean
❌ No schemas
❌ No queries
✅ Mental models only
This supports correctness without overfitting.

7. Design Decisions & Trade‑Offs (WHY DATA ⭐)
This section is mandatory.
Include:
Major architectural decisions
Trade‑offs considered
Alternatives rejected (and why)
Safety, compliance, or scalability drivers
Teach the LLM how Orion engineers think.

8. Security, Privacy & Compliance Principles
Explain:
Security posture (not implementation secrets)
Trust assumptions
Compliance constraints shaping the design
What Orion refuses to do for safety reasons
This prevents dangerous hallucinations.

9. Boundaries, Constraints & Non‑Goals (ANTI‑HALLUCINATION)
Be explicit:
What this product does NOT do
Known limitations
Constraints imposed by regulation or architecture
This section dramatically improves answer reliability.

10. Relationship to Other Orion Products
Explain:
How this product fits into the Orion ecosystem
What it depends on
What depends on it
What is shared vs unique
This enables cross‑product reasoning without confusion.

11. Version Awareness (LIGHT)
Only include:
Current vs deprecated behaviors (high‑level)
Major shifts (e.g., legacy → cloud)
No timelines, no roadmap.

